   274	
   275	## Statuses
   276	
   277	9 statuses: `backlog` → `analysis` → `to-dev` → `development` → `to-review` → `reviewing` → `done`. Plus `closed` and `blocked`.
   278	
   279	For full status flow, auto-promotion/reopen, blocked vs is_blocked — see [`references/statuses.md`](references/statuses.md).
   280	
   281	---
   282	
   283	## File Formats
   284	
   285	Each element directory contains two files:
   286	- **README.md** — static description (what the element is, scope, acceptance criteria). Does not change during execution.
   287	- **progress.md** — dynamic lifecycle journal (status, assignment, timestamps, dependencies, checklist, notes). Updated throughout execution.
   288	
   289	Dependencies are bidirectional and auto-escalate across parent boundaries.
   290	
   291	For detailed format specifications, field descriptions, and examples, see [`references/file-formats.md`](references/file-formats.md).
   292	
   293	---
   294	
   295	## Resources & Bugs
   296	
   297	Resources are linked to board elements via DSL mutations. Two types:
   298	- **Precondition** — inputs for the task (instructions, specs, design docs). Used by `task-board spawn` to compose agent prompts.
   299	- **Outcome** — work products (research results, implementation notes). Persisted for other agents/tasks to consume.
   300	
   301	```bash
   302	# Create resource
   303	task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md, content="...", type=precondition, description="Architecture design")'
   304	task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_results.md, content="...", type=outcome, description="Research findings")'
   305	
   306	# Replace existing resource
   307	task-board m 'update_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_results.md, content="revised findings", type=outcome, description="Research findings v2")'
   308	
   309	# Delete resource
   310	task-board m --confirm 'delete_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md)'
   311	```
   312	
   313	Resources are stored flat in `.task-board/.resources/<elementID>/` and referenced from `progress.md`. Bugs live inside stories alongside tasks.
   314	
   315	For resource workflow and bug tracking — see [`references/resources-and-bugs.md`](references/resources-and-bugs.md).
   316	
   317	---
   318	
   319	## Workflow
   320	
   321	### Full Development Cycle (MANDATORY)
   322	
   323	When the user asks to build/implement something, the agent MUST follow this end-to-end flow:
   324	
   325	#### Spec
   326	- Specs live in the `.spec/` directory (one or more `.md` files), not in a single `SPEC.md`
   327	- Create `.spec/` if it doesn't exist; add focused spec files per topic/feature (e.g. `.spec/auth.md`, `.spec/api.md`)
   328	- Clarify requirements with the user if anything is ambiguous
   329	- `.spec/` is the source of truth — all work traces back to it
   330	
   331	#### Plan on the Board
   332	- Create epics and stories: `task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=..., description="...")'`
   333	- Refine each element: query with `task-board q 'get(ID) { full }'`, clarify gaps, update via `task-board m 'set_details(ID, description="...")'`
   334	- No element should have placeholder text — description and AC must be complete and unambiguous
   335	
   336	#### Story Detailing, Phase Planning, Execution (MANDATORY)
   337	
   338	Full planning and execution workflow — story detailing, phase planning, user approval, pre-launch checklist, sub-agent execution, supervision, visualization — see [`references/planning-workflow.md`](references/planning-workflow.md).
   339	
   340	Key points:
   341	- **Story detailing before planning** — all stories must have tasks before phase planning
   342	- **Use `task-board q 'plan(...)'` as the canonical planning API** — it returns the planning model (scope, phases, critical path). Use `task-board plan` only as a local pretty-print / render / save facade over that same model. NEVER build phases manually or write plan files by hand
   343	- **Dump plan to `.planning/`** — after planning, save to `.planning/{YYMMDD}_{HHmmss}_{topic}.md` for session recovery. Use `task-board plan --save`
   344	- **User approval MANDATORY** — never start execution without user confirmation
   345	- **Pre-launch checklist** — model, status, assignment, concrete IDs, first command
   346	- **Coordinator is SUPERVISOR** — never writes code, only delegates to sub-agents
   347	
   348	#### Research / Analysis Tasks
   349	
   350	Research workflow, resource linking, document structure, status flow — see [`references/research-workflow.md`](references/research-workflow.md).
   351	
   352	Key points:
   353	- Research results are linked to board elements via `task-board m 'add_resource(..., type=outcome)'` on first write and `update_resource(...)` on revisions
   354	- Broadly useful research also persists in **`.research/`** directory (project-level)
   355	- Status flow: `backlog → analysis → to-review → reviewing → done` (skip `development`; coordinator spawns `task-board spawn TASK-... --role reviewer --background` after `to-review`)
   356	- Always link research output as an outcome resource on the task, and include the task ID in the resource name
   357	
   358	### Iterative Refinement (for individual elements)
   359	
   360	When creating ANY element (epic/story/task/bug), the agent MUST:
   361	
   362	1. **Create** element via `task-board m 'create(type=..., name=..., description="...")'`
   363	2. **Read** the element: `task-board q 'get(ID) { full }'`
   364	3. **Clarify** — if description is vague or has gaps, ask the user
   365	4. **Update** via `task-board m 'set_details(ID, description="...", ac="...")'`
   366	5. **Repeat** steps 2-4 until description is exhaustive
   367	6. Element is **ready** only when description and AC are complete and unambiguous
   368	
   369	### Project Start
   370	
   371	- Create elements: `task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=auth-system, description="...")'`
   372	- Create stories: `task-board m 'create(type=story, parent=EPIC-260218-abc, name=login)'`
   373	- Detail tasks: `task-board m 'create(type=task, parent=STORY-260218-abc, name=impl)'`
   374	- Set dependencies: `task-board m 'link(STORY-260218-def, blocked_by=STORY-260218-abc)'`
   375	- **Generate phases**: `task-board q 'plan(EPIC-260218-abc, mode=children)'` — only after all stories have tasks and dependencies are set
   376	
   377	### Spawning Agents for Tasks
   378	
   379	The **coordinator never writes code** — it delegates to tracked background child runs via `task-board spawn ... --background`.
   380	
   381	Treat [`references/tracked-background-spawn.md`](references/tracked-background-spawn.md) as the canonical operator-facing spawn contract. The guidance below is the workflow summary agents should follow.
   382	
   383	**`--role` is REQUIRED.** Every spawn must specify a role. Choose the role based on the task:
   384	
   385	| Task type | Role |
   386	|-----------|------|
   387	| Research, analysis, investigation | `--role researcher` |
   388	| Code implementation, bugfixes | `--role developer` |
   389	| Writing tests | `--role tester` |
   390	| Story decomposition, architecture | `--role solution-architect` |
   391	| Documentation | `--role doc-writer` |
   392	| Code review, quality check | `--role reviewer` |
   393	
   394	**Workflow:**
   395	
   396	1. **Preflight runtime** — run `task-board q 'project_config()'` before spawning so you know whether this cwd is using a local board or a remote profile
   397	2. **Prepare task** — ensure element has clear title, description, scope, AC
   398	3. **Add task-specific DoD on the board** — checklist items on the element are the task-specific DoD that spawn validates before launch
   399	   ```bash
   400	   task-board m 'add_checklist_item(TASK-260218-abc, text="Handle edge case X")'
   401	   task-board m 'add_checklist_item(TASK-260218-abc, text="Preserve existing API response shape")'
   402	   ```
   403	4. **Link instruction** (optional) — add precondition resource:
   404	   ```bash
   405	   # Inline text instruction
   406	   task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md, content="...", type=precondition, description="Implementation guide")'
   407	
   408	   # File or URL attachment
   409	   task-board resource add TASK-260218-abc ./TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md --type precondition
   410	
   411	   # Chat attachment only (no local path yet) — requires alexis-agents-infra:
   412	   # https://github.com/relux-works/alexis-agents-infra
   413	   agents-attachments materialize
   414	   task-board resource add TASK-260218-abc "$(agents-attachments path attachment-001)" --name TASK-260218-abc_attachment-001.bin --type precondition
   415	   ```
   416	5. **Spawn with role in background** — `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role developer --background` (auto-composes prompt from role + README + checklist DoD + precondition resources)
   417	   - With instruction validation: `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role developer --background --instruction TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md`
   418	   - Reviews are spawned too: `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role reviewer --background`
   419	6. **Capture the run id** — tracked background spawn returns `RUN-...`; use it as the coordinator handle for that child execution
   420	   - CLI output now prints non-blocking monitor commands with a seeded cursor (`RUN-ID:0`) and preserves the active `task-board` executable / board context

exec
/bin/zsh -lc "nl -ba /Users/alexis/.claude/skills/project-management/SKILL.md | sed -n '421,840p'" in /Users/alexis/src/relux-works/relux-analytics
 succeeded in 0ms:
   421	   - JSON output exposes the same self-contained contract under `observation` (`cursor`, `eventsCommand`, `watchCommand`, `waitCommand`, `inSessionDelivery`)
   422	7. **Monitor** — `task-board spawn status RUN-...`, `task-board spawn events RUN-... --cursor ...`, `task-board spawn watch RUN-...`, `task-board spawn wait RUN-...`, and `task-board q --format compact 'agents()'`
   423	   - Directive plane: `task-board spawn directives RUN-...` to inspect durable operator directives and `task-board spawn directive RUN-... <kind>` to request `cancel`, `pause_after_checkpoint`, `restart`, `reroute_after_checkpoint`, `request_progress`, or `nudge`
   424	8. **Review via child run** — when an implementer/tester/researcher sets `to-review`, treat that as "ready for review", not done. Spawn a review child with `--role reviewer --background`; the parent coordinates the review result and only then marks `done` or sends back to `to-dev`
   425	
   426	Spawn is task-centric:
   427	- Primary inputs are task ID + role
   428	- `task-board q 'project_config()'` is the supported preflight check before spawning or auditing
   429	- Agent selection follows the current runtime (Claude sessions -> `claude`, Codex sessions -> `codex`) and can be overridden with `--agent`
   430	- Model selection is optional
   431	- Task description comes from the board README
   432	- Task-specific DoD comes from the board checklist
   433	- Role baseline DoD is appended after task-specific DoD
   434	- Precondition resources carry additional instructions, screenshots, specs, and artifacts
   435	- Hidden legacy `--task-path` and `--dod-path` flags are compatibility-only appenders; they do not replace the board README/checklist workflow and should not be part of the normal contract
   436	- Spawn returns a tracked `RUN-...` handle; use `task-board spawn wait RUN-...` only after a run exists and the parent needs an explicit synchronization barrier
   437	- Spawn output includes coordinator observation hints for non-blocking monitoring (`watch`, `events --cursor RUN-ID:0`, `wait`) and keeps them runnable in the same executable / board context that produced the run
   438	- `task-board spawn --json` exposes the same contract in `observation.*`; `observation.inSessionDelivery=true` only when the current Codex orchestrator session was launched through `task-board codex`
   439	- Spawn run events use replay cursor tokens (`RUN-ID:seq`) so local CLI, TUI, and remote watchers can resume from the same durable position
   440	- Spawn directives are first-class durable records with acknowledgement state; use `spawn directive` / `spawn directives` instead of ad hoc notes for cancel/pause/restart/reroute intent
   441	- Watcher notifications are external observation surfaces by default; `task-board codex` adds runtime-native terminal delivery back into the active Codex thread
   442	- Soft directives are cooperative checkpoint signals only. Spawned agents can inspect them through `TASK_BOARD_RUN_ID` + `task-board spawn directives "$TASK_BOARD_RUN_ID"`; do not assume live in-session push
   443	- Coordinators must not wrap `task-board spawn` in `&`, `nohup`, or runtime background wrappers; `--background` already returns a tracked run
   444	- Spawn validates that the board task brief is usable: description and acceptance criteria must be real, not placeholders or one-line fluff
   445	- Repeated spawn on the same task must be idempotent: existing injected checklist items are not duplicated
   446	- When auditing spawn docs/help/source, exclude `.temp/**` from repo-wide searches so stale task-scoped worktrees do not look like current contract files
   447	
   448	### Model Selection Guide
   449	
   450	**Always use top-tier models.** A bug from a weaker model on a simple task will cost you 10x more to debug on a complex one.
   451	
   452	| Task type | Agent | Model | --reasoning-effort | Notes |
   453	|-----------|-------|-------|--------------------|-------|
   454	| Code implementation | codex | gpt-5.5 (default) | **xhigh** | Codex spawn enables live web search by default; do not use `minimal` |
   455	| Code implementation (override) | codex | gpt-5.3-codex | **xhigh** | Use explicitly when you want the coding-specialized variant |
   456	| Fast code iteration | codex | gpt-5.3-codex-spark | **xhigh** | Valid tracked background spawn option when speed matters more than depth |
   457	| Thinking/architecture | codex | **gpt-5.5 (default)** | **xhigh** | Use the same top-tier default here too |
   458	| All tasks | claude | claude-opus-4-6 (default) | - | Always opus. No exceptions |
   459	
   460	Other models may be available, but the recommended board workflow is still to use the strongest model for the chosen agent.
   461	
   462	**Budget: unlimited by default.** Don't pass `--budget` unless the user explicitly asks to cap spending. Let agents finish their work — a $5 cap on a $3 task means a failed half-done agent + a retry that costs $6 total. Unlimited is cheaper than retries.
   463	
   464	The CLI validates model choices and warns (never blocks) when:
   465	- Model is unknown (forward-compatible — new models pass through)
   466	- Model belongs to a different agent type
   467	- Model benefits from `--reasoning-effort` but none is set
   468	- `--reasoning-effort` is set on a model that doesn't support it
   469	
   470	### Working on a Task (as sub-agent)
   471	
   472	1. Assign + start → `task-board m 'assign(TASK-260218-abc, agent=agent-name); set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=development)'`
   473	2. Work until the task is genuinely complete or objectively blocked. Do not stop with the task parked in `analysis`, `development`, `testing`, or `reviewing` just because one local action finished.
   474	3. Stop and escalate if completion would require a forced fit: document the constraint, failed assumption, viable options, and exact human/product/architecture decision needed. Do not pile on compensating tests, stubs, flags, or priority rules to make an invalid model appear to work.
   475	4. Update checklist → `task-board m 'check_item(TASK-260218-abc, item=1)'`
   476	5. Save results → `task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_results.md, content="...", type=outcome, description="Implementation notes")'`
   477	6. Ready for review → `task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=to-review)'`
   478	7. Or blocked → `task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=blocked); set_notes(TASK-260218-abc, text="Blocked: concrete blocker and evidence")'`
   479	8. Orchestrator confirms producer evidence, spawns a tracked reviewer child (`task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role reviewer --background`), waits or monitors the returned `RUN-...`, then routes by the reviewer-child verdict: accepted → `done`, changes requested → `to-dev`
   480	
   481	Human-facing language is part of the contract: a producer ending at `to-review` says "ready for review" or "handed off to review", not "done"/"complete"/"finished"/"final"/"готово". Only a reviewer/coordinator may call the board task done, and only after the board status is actually `done`.
   482	
   483	### Dependencies
   484	
   485	```bash
   486	# TASK-B depends on TASK-A
   487	task-board m 'link(TASK-260218-def, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc)'
   488	
   489	# CLI will refuse to move TASK-B to development while TASK-A is not done
   490	task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-def, status=development)'
   491	# Error: cannot start TASK-260218-def — blocked by: TASK-260218-abc
   492	
   493	# Remove dependency
   494	task-board m 'unlink(TASK-260218-def, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc)'
   495	```
   496	
   497	### Board Review
   498	
   499	```bash
   500	# Queries (use --format compact for token efficiency)
   501	task-board q 'schema()'                                                          # discover fields, presets, operations
   502	task-board q 'project_config()'                                                  # confirm this repo is local or remote before agent work
   503	task-board q --format compact 'summary()'                                        # quick overview
   504	task-board q --format compact 'get(TASK-260218-abc) { full }'                    # full element details
   505	task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, status=development) { overview }'  # what's in progress
   506	task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, blocked=true) { id name status }'  # what's blocked
   507	task-board q --format compact 'agents()'                                         # agent dashboard
   508	task-board q --format compact 'plan(EPIC-260218-abc, mode=children)'             # execution phases
   509	
   510	# Full-text search (local only)
   511	task-board grep "AudioRecorder"
   512	
   513	# Validation (local only)
   514	task-board validate
   515	```
   516	
   517	---
   518	
   519	## Querying & Mutating the Board
   520	
   521	Three primary access modes following the [agent-facing-api](https://github.com/relux-works/skill-agent-facing-api) pattern — all through one CLI binary:
   522	
   523	- **`q` (query DSL)** — structured reads: `task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, status=development) { overview }'`
   524	- **`grep` (full-text search)** — scoped text search: `task-board grep "AudioRecorder"` (local only)
   525	- **`m` (mutation DSL)** — structured writes: `task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=done)'`
   526	
   527	Plus a CLI plan facade for pretty-print / render / save: `task-board plan ...`, and local-only utilities such as `validate` (structure check).
   528	
   529	Field presets: `minimal` (id, status), `default` (id, name, status), `overview` (+ assignee, parent), `full` (all 18 fields), `progress` (status, checklist, notes, blocked), `planning` (status, blocks, parent).
   530	
   531	When mentioning board elements in human-facing responses, always include both the concrete ID and the human-readable title/name. This applies to epics, stories, tasks, and bugs. ID-only references are not enough for people scanning the chat because they should not have to resolve identifiers manually.
   532	
   533	For DSL operations, mutations reference, field projection, and decision table — see [`references/querying.md`](references/querying.md).
   534	
