   954	
   955	# Part 3: Agent Tracking
   956	
   957	## Assigning Agents
   958	
   959	```bash
   960	# Assign agent to element
   961	task-board m 'assign(STORY-260218-abc, agent=agent-1)'
   962	
   963	# Remove assignment
   964	task-board m 'unassign(STORY-260218-abc)'
   965	```
   966	
   967	## Agent Dashboard
   968	
   969	```bash
   970	# Show active agents
   971	task-board q --format compact 'agents()'
   972	
   973	# Custom stale threshold (minutes)
   974	task-board q --format compact 'agents(stale=60)'
   975	```
   976	
   977	Dashboard shows: agent name, scope, status, child progress (done/total), last update time.
   978	
   979	## Sub-Agent Workflow
   980	
   981	1. Coordinator breaks work into stories, assigns agents:
   982	   ```bash
   983	   task-board m 'assign(STORY-260218-abc, agent=agent-1); assign(STORY-260218-def, agent=agent-2)'
   984	   ```
   985	2. Each sub-agent works on its scope, updating task statuses
   986	3. Coordinator monitors: `task-board q --format compact 'agents()'`
   987	4. When all done — agents disappear from dashboard
   988	
   989	## Agent Roles
   990	
   991	Roles define what an agent does, which skills it needs, what statuses it drives, and its definition of done.
   992	
   993	### Role Registry
   994	
   995	Roles are defined in `.roles/<role-name>/` directories:
   996	
   997	```
   998	.roles/
   999	├── developer/
  1000	│   ├── role.md        # frontmatter + markdown body
  1001	│   └── skills.md      # optional: skill list
  1002	├── researcher/
  1003	│   ├── role.md
  1004	│   └── skills.md
  1005	├── tester/
  1006	│   └── role.md
  1007	└── ...
  1008	```
  1009	
  1010	**role.md frontmatter format:**
  1011	
  1012	```yaml
  1013	---
  1014	name: developer
  1015	description: Writes code, fixes bugs, writes tests
  1016	archetype: implementer          # implementer | analyst | reviewer | tester
  1017	start_status: development       # status set on spawn launch
  1018	end_status: to-review           # role handoff status; for producers this means ready for review, not done
  1019	dod:                            # definition of done — added to board checklist on spawn
  1020	  - Code written per task description and AC
  1021	  - Relevant tests written for new or changed behavior and passing
  1022	  - Relevant build/validation commands run after changes and build not broken
  1023	skills:                         # optional: inline skill list (merged with skills.md)
  1024	  - go-tui-testing-tools
  1025	---
  1026	
  1027	# developer
  1028	
  1029	## Description
  1030	Writes code — features, bugfixes, refactoring. Writes tests for the code produced.
  1031	
  1032	## Standing Orders
  1033	1. Add or update relevant tests for changed behavior.
  1034	2. Run the relevant tests before handoff.
  1035	3. Run the relevant build or validation command after changes.
  1036	
  1037	## Deliverable
  1038	Code + tests.
  1039	...
  1040	```
  1041	
  1042	**skills.md format** (optional, merged with `skills:` in frontmatter):
  1043	```markdown
  1044	## Required
  1045	- project-management
  1046	- go-tui-testing-tools
  1047	
  1048	## Domain
  1049	- core-data (when working on persistence)
  1050	- swiftui (when building UI)
  1051	```
  1052	
  1053	**Resolution order** (`LoadRole`):
  1054	1. Project-local directory: `<workDir>/.roles/<name>/role.md`
  1055	2. Project-local single file: `<workDir>/.roles/<name>.md`
  1056	3. Global directory: `~/.roles/<name>/role.md`
  1057	4. Global single file: `~/.roles/<name>.md`
  1058	
  1059	Directory format takes priority over single file. Project-local takes priority over global.
  1060	
  1061	**Global role installation:** `scripts/setup.sh` copies the bundled roles from `.roles/` into `~/.roles/`, making them available in any project without a local `.roles/` directory.
  1062	
  1063	**Available roles:**
  1064	
  1065	| Role | Archetype | Start → End Status |
  1066	|------|-----------|-------------------|
  1067	| `researcher` | analyst | `analysis` → `to-review` |
  1068	| `developer` | implementer | `development` → `to-review` |
  1069	| `tester` | tester | `development` → `to-review` |
  1070	| `solution-architect` | analyst | `analysis` → `to-review` |
  1071	| `doc-writer` | implementer | `development` → `to-review` |
  1072	| `reviewer` | reviewer | `reviewing` → `done` |
  1073	| `orchestrator` | analyst | orchestration-only, no default status transition |
  1074	| `coordinator` | analyst | orchestration-only, no default status transition |
  1075	
  1076	### How Roles Work with Spawn
  1077	
  1078	**`--role` is REQUIRED.** Spawning without a role produces a crippled agent with no identity, no skills, no DoD, and no lifecycle commands. Always specify a role.
  1079	
  1080	The spawn pipeline:
  1081	1. Loads role config from `.roles/<role>/role.md`
  1082	2. Loads task metadata (README + precondition resources)
  1083	3. Computes pre-launch board updates:
  1084	   - Sets element status to `start_status` (e.g. `development` for developer)
  1085	   - Sets agent name with archetype prefix, e.g. `[implementer] developer (codex)`
  1086	   - Adds DoD items as checklist entries on the board element
  1087	4. Assembles prompt from template: role body, skills, DoD, status commands, task metadata
  1088	5. Persists prompt and spawn-run state under `.temp/prompts/` and `.temp/spawn-runs/RUN-.../`
  1089	6. Returns the `RUN-...` handle immediately
  1090	7. Background runner claims a queue slot under `spawn.max_parallel`, launches the real child agent, streams logwork, and executes completion hooks
  1091	8. Agent gets FIRST command (set start status) and LAST role-handoff command (set end status) in prompt
  1092	
  1093	```bash
  1094	# Spawn researcher for a research task (status → analysis)
  1095	task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role researcher --background
  1096	
  1097	# Spawn developer for implementation (status → development, DoD → checklist)
  1098	task-board spawn TASK-260218-def --role developer --background
  1099	
  1100	# Runtime-aware agent selection:
  1101	# - from Claude session -> claude
  1102	# - from Codex session -> codex
  1103	task-board spawn TASK-260218-xyz --role developer --background
  1104	
  1105	# Spawn reviewer (status → reviewing)
  1106	task-board spawn TASK-260218-ghi --role reviewer --background
  1107	
  1108	# Spawn orchestrator/coordinator for decomposition / orchestration / verification
  1109	task-board spawn TASK-260218-jkl --role orchestrator --background
  1110	task-board spawn TASK-260218-jkl --role coordinator --background
  1111	```
  1112	
  1113	`orchestrator` / `coordinator` is the special supervisor role: it should create or refine tasks, spawn specialist roles, guard architecture, monitor delivery quality, and verify outputs before driving items to `done`. It should not do specialist implementation directly when delegation is appropriate.
  1114	
  1115	For coordinator orchestration:
  1116	- fan out children with `task-board spawn TASK-... --role ... --background`
  1117	- keep the returned `RUN-...` ids
  1118	- use `task-board spawn status/wait` as explicit synchronization points
  1119	- sequence dependent work: wait for producer runs, verify outcome resources, then spawn reviewer/consumer runs
  1120	- do not shell-background `task-board spawn`; that duplicates the async layer and makes completion handling worse
  1121	
  1122	### Skill Injection
  1123	
  1124	Skills are injected as references (paths), not inlined into prompts. Both Claude and Codex use lazy body loading — only skill metadata (name + description) loads at startup (~50-200 tokens per skill). Full SKILL.md body loads on-demand when the agent decides it's relevant.
  1125	
  1126	This means one `developer` role can reference many skills (swiftui, core-data, go-testing-tools, etc.) without context bloat — the agent picks what's needed for the specific task.
  1127	
  1128	## Sub-Agent Prompt Templates
  1129	
  1130	For sub-agent prompt templates (decomposition agent, implementation agent, coordinator review workflow), see [`references/sub-agent-templates.md`](references/sub-agent-templates.md).
  1131	
  1132	Key points covered there:
  1133	- Reality check: how to maximize sub-agent compliance with task-board updates
  1134	- Decomposition agent template (for story detailing phase)
  1135	- Implementation agent template (for execution phase)
  1136	- Coordinator review workflow (approve / return for rework)
  1137	
  1138	## Spawning Tracked Background Runs
  1139	
  1140	**Tracked background children are separate CLI processes** (`claude -p` / `codex exec`), each with its own context window. They are not internal sub-agents. Use `task-board spawn ... --background` to launch with automatic board integration and `RUN-...` tracking.
  1141	
  1142	**`--role` is REQUIRED** — the role drives the agent's identity, skills, status lifecycle, and definition of done.
  1143	
  1144	Use `task-board q 'project_config()'` as the preflight check before spawn or spawn-contract review, and treat [`references/tracked-background-spawn.md`](references/tracked-background-spawn.md) as the canonical operator-facing contract. The durable wait/completion invariant lives in [`.specs/spawn-runtime-completion.md`](.specs/spawn-runtime-completion.md).
  1145	
  1146	`project_config().codex.session.auto_continue` surfaces the effective Codex anti-stall defaults for this cwd. Those settings currently apply only to `task-board codex`; explicit `task-board codex --auto-continue*` flags override config when provided.
  1147	
  1148	**Template-based prompt composition is board-centric:** `spawn` composes the prompt from the role template plus board state:
  1149	- task description comes from the element README
  1150	- task-specific DoD comes from checklist items already present on the element
  1151	- role baseline DoD is appended after task-specific DoD
  1152	- precondition resources carry additional instructions and artifacts
  1153	
  1154	Hidden legacy `--task-path` / `--dod-path` flags are compatibility-only appenders. They are not the normal workflow and should not be treated as required task inputs.
  1155	
  1156	If the element has no task-specific DoD on the board, spawn should fail with a clear validation error instead of launching an underspecified agent.
  1157	
  1158	The prompt also includes:
  1159	1. Role config (identity, skills, DoD, status commands)
  1160	2. Task README fields (title, scope, AC)
  1161	3. Precondition resources attached to the task (loaded and injected into the prompt)
  1162	4. A Go template (project-local `.agents/spawn-template.md` or embedded default)
  1163	
  1164	**Orchestrator monitoring:** `task-board spawn ... --background` creates a tracked background runner, persists run state under `.temp/spawn-runs/`, and returns a `RUN-...` identifier immediately. The spawn response also includes coordinator-facing observation hints (text and `--json observation.*`) with a seeded resume cursor (`RUN-ID:0`) and watch/events/wait commands that preserve the active `task-board` executable plus resolved board context. `task-board spawn events RUN-...` replays durable run events with resume cursors (`RUN-ID:seq`), `task-board spawn watch RUN-...` follows the same stream, and `task-board spawn wait RUN-...` waits on persisted terminal state. Watcher notifications are external observation surfaces; they do not inject text into the active orchestrator session unless a runtime-specific adapter exists. The background runner is the process that blocks on the real child agent, executes the completion hook, and only then marks the run terminal.
  1165	
  1166	**Concurrency policy:** shared spawn runtime settings live in `task-board.config.json -> spawn`. `spawn.max_parallel` limits how many tracked background runners may actively execute child-agent work at once. When omitted, the default limit is `20`.
  1167	
  1168	**Codex anti-stall policy:** project-local defaults for interactive Codex sessions live in `task-board.config.json -> codex.session.auto_continue`. Use that section for team defaults, and override per launch with `task-board codex --auto-continue`, `--auto-continue-delay`, `--auto-continue-max-nudges`, or `--auto-continue-prompt`. This v1 scope is `task-board codex` only, not generic `spawn --agent codex`.
  1169	
  1170	**Observed load-smoke:** with `spawn.max_parallel = 20`, a local smoke run of `30` fake-codex tasks yielded `20 running / 10 queued` on the first sample, then `20 completed / 10 running / 0 queued`, then full completion with `0` failures. Treat this as the expected queue shape for small homogeneous tasks.
  1171	
  1172	For spawn flags, audit hygiene, template customization, orchestrator patterns, failure modes, and manual launch fallback — see [`references/tracked-background-spawn.md`](references/tracked-background-spawn.md).
  1173	
  1174	---

