# Resources

Resources are linked to board elements via explicit CRUD operations. They are stored centrally in `.task-board/.resources/` (local) or in MinIO / filesystem storage (remote board-server).

## Resource Types

| Type | Purpose | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| **precondition** | Inputs needed before work starts | Design docs, specs, instructions, API schemas |
| **outcome** | Results produced by work | Research findings, implementation notes, analysis |

## Commands

```bash
# Create a resource
task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_design.md, type=precondition, content="...", description="Architecture design")'
task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_results.md, type=outcome, content="...", description="Research findings")'

# Replace an existing resource
task-board m 'update_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_results.md, type=outcome, content="revised findings", description="Research findings v2")'
task-board resource update TASK-260218-abc ./TASK-260218-abc_results.md --type outcome

# Delete a resource (destructive — requires --confirm)
task-board m --confirm 'delete_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_design.md)'
task-board resource delete TASK-260218-abc TASK-260218-abc_design.md

# View resources on an element
task-board q --format compact 'get(TASK-260218-abc) { full }'
```

## Storage

Resources are stored flat in `.task-board/.resources/<elementID>/<name>`:

```
.task-board/.resources/
├── TASK-260203-g7h8i9/
│   ├── design.md           # precondition
│   └── results.md          # outcome
└── STORY-260203-d4e5f6/
    └── research.md         # outcome
```

References are tracked in `progress.md` as markdown links:
```markdown
## Precondition Resources
- [design.md](board-resource://TASK-260203-g7h8i9/precondition/design.md) — Architecture design

## Outcome Resources
- [results.md](board-resource://TASK-260203-g7h8i9/outcome/results.md) — Research findings
```

## Spawn Integration

Precondition resources are automatically injected into agent prompts by `task-board spawn`. The spawn template renders each precondition resource's content as a section in the prompt. This means:

1. Attach instructions/specs as precondition resources to a task
2. Run `task-board spawn TASK-XX --role developer --background` — agent gets everything automatically
3. Agent saves results via `task-board m 'add_resource(..., type=outcome)'` on first write, then `update_resource(...)` for revisions

## Best Practices

- **Use preconditions for agent instructions** — attach design docs, specs, or step-by-step instructions before spawning
- **Use outcomes for work products** — research findings, analysis, implementation notes
- **Use explicit create/update/delete** — `add_resource` / `resource add` must not silently overwrite; use `update_resource` / `resource update` when replacing an existing payload
- **Always use board commands** — never create/edit resource files or progress.md resource sections manually
- **Name descriptively with task scope** — `TASK-260218-abc_architecture-design.md` not `doc.md`
- **Add descriptions** — the `description=` param adds a one-line description shown in spawn prompts

---

# Bugs

Bugs are elements of the board, living inside stories alongside tasks.

```bash
# Create bug
task-board m 'create(type=bug, parent=STORY-260218-abc, name=crash-on-start, description="App crashes when starting recording")'

# Track like any element
task-board m 'set_status(BUG-260218-abc, status=development)'
task-board m 'add_checklist_item(BUG-260218-abc, text="Reproduce the issue")'
task-board m 'add_checklist_item(BUG-260218-abc, text="Find root cause")'
task-board m 'add_checklist_item(BUG-260218-abc, text="Write fix")'
task-board m 'add_checklist_item(BUG-260218-abc, text="Add regression test")'
```

